      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Correspondence</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The Correspondence series is the largest in the collection. It spans the years 1919-1967, but the greatest concentration of letters is between the years 1960 and 1963. The majority of the letters during these years are routine responses to correspondence from readers of his column. For this reason, correspondence from earlier years tends to be more interesting and diverse. His correspondence includes many letters from important people of his day, especially within the state of Michigan. While many of these letters are simply acknowledgements of Manning's newspaper articles, Manning did have a fairly substantial exchange of letters with Frank Murphy, James Couzens, and his aunt Margaret Manning Couzens (the wife of James Couzens) during the 1930's. He was also on good terms with William Randolph Hearst (Senior and Junior) and Henry Ford II.</p>
        </scopecontent>
